#Day 2

## Age Group Analysis

Average claim amounts varied across age groups.

| Age Group | Average Claim Amount |
| --------- | -------------------- |
| 15-25     | 53,873               |
| 25-35     | 50,361               |
| 35-45     | 52,996               |
| 45-55     | 54,721               |
| 55+       | 58,997               |

### Key Observation

Policyholders aged 55+ exhibited the highest average claim amount, 
while the 25-35 age group showed the lowest average claim cost.


## Incident Severity Analysis

| Incident Severity | Average Claim Amount |
| ----------------- | -------------------- |
| Major Damage      | 64,067               |
| Total Loss        | 62,081               |
| Minor Damage      | 48,643               |
| Trivial Damage    | 5,302                |

### Key Observation

Incident severity was a major driver of claim costs.
Major Damage and Total Loss incidents generated substantially higher claims than Minor or Trivial Damage incidents.


## Premium vs Claim Amount

Correlation between annual premium and total claim amount:

0.009

### Key Observation

There was virtually no linear relationship between annual premiums and claim amounts,
suggesting that claim costs may be influenced by factors beyond premium levels alone.


## Claim Component Analysis

| Claim Component | Average Amount |
|----------------|---------------|
| Injury Claim | 7,433 |
| Property Claim | 7,400 |
| Vehicle Claim | 37,929 |

### Key Observation

Vehicle claims represent the largest component of total losses, averaging 37,929 per claim.
Injury and property claims contribute significantly less, averaging approximately 7,400 each.


## Fraud Analysis

| Fraud Reported | Average Claim Amount | Count |
|---------------|--------------------|------|
| N | 50,289 | 753 |
| Y | 60,302 | 247 |

### Key Observation

Fraudulent claims accounted for 24.7% of all claims and exhibited 
average claim amounts approximately 20% higher than non-fraudulent claims.


## Fraud by Incident Severity

Fraud rates varied significantly across severity categories.

| Severity | Fraud Rate |
|----------|------------|
| Major Damage | 60.5% |
| Minor Damage | 10.7% |
| Total Loss | 12.9% |
| Trivial Damage | 6.7% |

### Key Observation

Major Damage incidents exhibited an exceptionally high fraud rate of 60.5%, substantially exceeding all other severity categories. 
This suggests that severity may be an important indicator for fraud risk assessment.

